    "descripcionEs": "La malaria del viajero es una enfermedad parasitaria potencialmente mortal causada por protozoos del genero Plasmodium, transmitida al ser humano a traves de la picadura de mosquitos hembra del genero Anopheles infectados. Existen cinco especies que infectan al humano: P. falciparum (la mas letal y prevalente en Africa subsahariana), P. vivax (la mas extendida globalmente), P. ovale, P. malariae y P. knowlesi. El periodo de incubacion varia segun la especie, desde 7 dias para P. falciparum hasta 30 dias o mas para P. vivax y P. ovale, que pueden formar hipnozoitos hepaticos latentes capaces de causar recaidas meses o anos despues de la infeccion inicial. Los viajeros no inmunes procedentes de zonas no endemicas presentan un riesgo significativamente mayor de desarrollar formas graves de la enfermedad, incluyendo malaria cerebral, anemia severa, insuficiencia renal aguda, sindrome de dificultad respiratoria aguda y coagulacion intravascular diseminada. La Organizacion Mundial de la Salud estima que aproximadamente 12,000 casos de malaria se diagnostican anualmente en viajeros que regresan a paises no endemicos, con una tasa de mortalidad del 1-5% en casos de P. falciparum no tratados oportunamente.",
    "descripcionEn": "Traveler's malaria is a potentially fatal parasitic disease caused by protozoa of the genus Plasmodium, transmitted to humans through the bite of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes. Five species infect humans: P. falciparum (the most lethal and prevalent in sub-Saharan Africa), P. vivax (the most widespread globally), P. ovale, P. malariae, and P. knowlesi. The incubation period varies by species, from 7 days for P. falciparum to 30 days or more for P. vivax and P. ovale, which can form latent hepatic hypnozoites capable of causing relapses months or years after the initial infection. Non-immune travelers from non-endemic areas have a significantly higher risk of developing severe forms of the disease, including cerebral malaria, severe anemia, acute renal failure, acute respiratory distress syndrome, and disseminated intravascular coagulation. The World Health Organization estimates that approximately 12,000 malaria cases are diagnosed annually in travelers returning to non-endemic countries, with a mortality rate of 1-5% in P. falciparum cases not treated promptly.",
